const t=[{slug:"what-to-do-burst-pipe",title:"Burst Pipe? Do These 4 Things Before the Plumber Arrives",excerpt:"A burst pipe can release hundreds of litres an hour. The four steps you take in the first five minutes make the biggest difference to the damage.",date:"2026-06-10",readingTime:"4 min read",image:"/images/emergency.svg",imageAlt:"Dark industrial pipework under emergency lighting",body:[{h:"1. Turn off the water at the stopcock",p:"Your internal stopcock is usually under the kitchen sink, in a downstairs toilet or cupboard, or where the mains enters the house. Turn it clockwise until it stops. If it’s seized, don’t force it hard enough to snap it — move to the outside stop valve at the boundary of your property."},{h:"2. Open the cold taps",p:"Once the mains is off, open your cold taps to drain the pipes quickly. This drops the pressure and slows the leak dramatically while the system empties."},{h:"3. Kill electricity near the water",p:"If water is anywhere near sockets, light fittings or your consumer unit, switch off the affected circuits. Never touch electrics with wet hands."},{h:"4. Contain and photograph",p:"Use towels and containers to limit spread, move valuables, and take photos as you go — they help your insurer and help us diagnose the failure. Then call a plumber and describe exactly what you see."}]},{slug:"why-drains-keep-blocking",title:"Why Your Drain Keeps Blocking (and What Actually Fixes It)",excerpt:"Clearing the same blockage every few months? The blockage is the symptom. Here are the usual underlying causes and the fixes that end the cycle.",date:"2026-05-18",readingTime:"5 min read",image:"/images/drainage.svg",imageAlt:"Underground drainage channel with flowing water",body:[{h:"The usual suspects",p:"Recurring blockages almost always trace back to one of a few causes: fat and grease congealing at a cool point in the run, scale narrowing older pipes, a sagging or back-falling section that lets solids settle, root intrusion at a joint, or a partially collapsed section snagging debris."},{h:"Why re-clearing isn’t a fix",p:"Rodding or plunging clears the symptom but leaves the cause. If the pipe has a low spot or a damaged section, the next blockage is already forming the day after the clearance."},{h:"What a proper diagnosis looks like",p:"A professional inspection follows the whole run, identifies where and why material is stopping, and matches the fix to the cause — descaling, re-laying a short section, or simply changing what goes down the sink. Ask for a plain-English explanation of the cause, not just a clearance."}]},{slug:"signs-of-hidden-leak",title:"6 Early Warning Signs of a Hidden Water Leak",excerpt:"Hidden leaks can run for months before they show. These six signs let you catch one early — before the ceiling does the telling.",date:"2026-04-02",readingTime:"4 min read",image:"/images/leak.svg",imageAlt:"Water tracing along a copper pipe joint",body:[{h:"Watch for these signs",p:"Unexplained increases in your water bill; a water meter that moves when everything is off; damp, musty smells in one area; paint or plaster that bubbles or stains; warm patches on floors (a hot-water pipe leak); and reduced pressure at one tap or shower."},{h:"The meter test",p:"Turn off every tap and appliance, note the meter reading, wait 30 minutes without using water, and check again. Movement means water is going somewhere it shouldn’t."},{h:"Why early matters",p:"Water follows joists and cavities, so damage appears far from the source and grows quietly. Tracing a leak early is a small, tidy job; waiting for a stained ceiling usually isn’t."}]}];function s(e){return t.find(a=>a.slug===e)}export{t as b,s as g};
